FDIC Bank Failure Analysis (2000–2023)
Tools: Python · pandas · matplotlib
Data: FDIC Failed Bank List (live federal dataset)

Overview
Analysis of FDIC bank failure data to understand the scale, geography, and acquisition patterns of U.S. bank failures — with a focus on the 2008 financial crisis. The central finding: nearly every bank that failed during the crisis was acquired by another institution, meaning the crisis represented a massive consolidation event as much as a collapse.
Key Findings
Failures and acquisitions track almost perfectly.
Plotting failed banks against acquired banks per year reveals the two lines are nearly identical — the overwhelming majority of failed banks were absorbed by surviving institutions rather than simply closed. This held true even at the peak of the crisis in 2008–2010.
The 2008 crisis produced a failure spike with no modern parallel.
Bank failures rose sharply beginning in 2008 and peaked around 2010, dwarfing failure rates in every other year in the dataset. The post-2010 decline was equally steep.
A small number of acquirers absorbed a disproportionate share of failures.
The top acquiring institutions — led by Centennial Bank, Fidelity Bank, and First NBC Bank — each absorbed multiple failed banks, suggesting strategic consolidation behavior rather than incidental acquisition.
Some acquirers later failed themselves.
A subset of banks that acquired failed institutions subsequently appeared on the FDIC failed list themselves — notably First NBC Bank, which acquired two banks before its own 2017 failure. This points to acquisition-driven risk accumulation as a failure pathway.
Florida, Georgia, and Illinois were the hardest-hit states.
Geographic concentration of failures was pronounced in Sun Belt and Midwest states, reflecting regional exposure to real estate and commercial lending losses.
Atlanta, Chicago, and Orlando led by city.
Failure concentration in specific metro areas reflects both market size and local real estate bubble dynamics.
Methods

Pulled live data directly from FDIC public API endpoint
Parsed and cleaned closing dates, normalized institution name strings for join matching
Identified acquirers-that-later-failed via string matching between acquiring institution and failed bank name columns
Aggregated by year, state, city, and acquiring institution for pattern analysis
Visualized with matplotlib

Data Source
FDIC Failed Bank List — updated regularly by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation.
https://www.fdic.gov/bank/individual/failed/banklist.csv
